##A Wuhan native who moves to the North decides to move

WECHAT dandureading

Function introduction single reading is a brand publication of one-way space, which unites a new generation of writers and readers. Its content is mainly fiction, poetry, cultural criticism, ideological essays, non-fiction reports and works of art, respect quiet, deep, elegant reading, respect sober, unique, dynamic voice, committed to become a source of ideas for young people around the world.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
After leaving the newsroom last summer, Raven, a former single-reader editor, remained in Beijing, where she continued to work. This Spring Festival, the crow did not plan to go home, also declined a friend's travel invitation, but continue to stationed in Beijing. To her surprise, the arrival of the COVID-19 epidemic and her status as a native of Wuhan made the Spring Festival a troubled time.

The new Beipiao diary

By Ravens

One

February 3, the first day of telecommuting, the fifth day of sleeping in Beijing. The hostel is in Chaoyang District, 16 km from a beijing-rented community, a one-bedroom flat that sits idle in the homes of Friends of friends.

At 9 p.m. on Jan. 29, roommate and I arrived at our temporary home in a car driven by my roommate's parents from Hebei Province. Three hours earlier, at 6 p.m. the same day, roommate and I got a call from our landlord, roughly saying we needed to move out of the neighborhood immediately tonight, or the neighborhood committee would "force us to leave" because the residents were panicking. Roommate and I were perplexed by the news. After all, we didn't get a call from the neighborhood clerk until 5 p.m. and were told to stay home for 14 days. I also talked to him about walking the dog in the neighborhood. Of course, I didn't forget his opening line, "residents reported you were out of town for four days. ".

A little further back in time. January 29 at 2:00 p.m. , and roommates to the Neighborhood Committee and the police station registered personal information. To avoid pleasantries, I volunteered to tell the clerk that I was from Wuhan, but I never left Beijing during the Spring Festival, and showed the refunds for my planned trip to and from Wuhan. The roommate explained that she traveled to and from Hebei during the Spring Festival. Apart from her parents, she had little contact with others. The other party advised us not to worry, they just routine, asked if we have taken temperature AH, body is abnormal, remember to make time to bring a photo to apply for a residence permit. We said we took a temperature, there's nothing wrong with it, and we've been too lazy to get a residence permit.

Out of the neighborhood, and roommates to discuss the convenience store to buy toast. I asked roommate if I was imagining it. It felt like they were all looking at us. I went to two convenience stores and didn't get any toast. I got a phone call from the neighborhood committee clerk. He asked me if I had received any phone calls from the police. I said No. He said if the police asked you if your body temperature was normal, you would say normal. I said yes, he said, "why don't you come back here and take one? " I said, "okay. ". After two minutes, he called again, he said forget you do not come, if you ask in the neighborhood committee took a temperature you said yes, I said yes. Hung up the phone and turned to his roommate and said, Oh, my God, it's really up and down the next look.

The landlord aunt heard our confusion and further told us that the situation now is that the Neighborhood Committee thinks you are Ok and the police station thinks you are OK, but the residents think you are OK. And why is that? Because you're from Wuhan. Repeatedly and the landlord stressed the fact that there is no Beijing, to the neighborhood director's phone. The director said, we're not forcing you to move, we're suggesting you move, this is a very special time, the residents are very emotional, if you do not move, we can not guarantee your safety. So we made several phone calls back and forth, and asked several friends. Still in the middle of the night, in the sight of the residents who were actually supervising the work on the street, and in the vulgar language, we were patted on the shoulder by the director of the Neighborhood Committee and said, knowing that you are wronged, don't let your parents worry Ah, "the old exhortation, rolled up the quilt, left.

Mandatory, suggested, familiar? A never-ending, infallible word play.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Two

February 4, Spring, Beijing two days before the snow has left little. With the help of my friends, my roommate and I didn't go back to Hebei with their parents, but with their friends, we moved into a completely unfamiliar area and entered a gray area by taking temperature gun measurements at the entrance of the community.

At last, I was no longer just a spectator to the epidemic. It's no longer just Weibo and reports, reminding Internet citizens in Wuhan that family and friends wear masks and wash their hands frequently.

Roommate and I are taking this in very different directions. It can even be said that our only consensus is that we are legitimate and reasonable in the whole affair, and that the result of the violation of the individual's right of residence because of the household registration (actually caused) is stupid and lazy. But how to deal with this injustice, and what to do at what point in time, we have shown greater disagreement. Roommate felt that small sacrifices in a pandemic were not to be ignored, and I understood everything, always thinking that I was nothing compared to the millions of people.

On January 30, after a voluntary complaint from our roommate, we contacted two media outlets and learned that many returnees in Beijing were facing similar situations; we called the 12345 to further confirm the regulations regarding the segregation of returnees and, alas, we didn't really break any laws and regulations; we prepared materials on how to deal with people returning to Beijing, and finally compiled them into a popular version of the Public Protection Guide, with excerpts compiled by the disease prevention and Control Bureau of the National Health Council, a section of the guidelines for public protection against COVID-19 pneumonia, compiled by the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention; The mobile phone to intercept the bullet train refund voucher, e-shopping list, Didi taxi orders, the number of the day, call records, chat records, compiled into a "moved households Spring Festival Travel Records" PDF, and Collated Public Protection Guide together to the Director of the Neighborhood Committee, hope to have the opportunity to chat with residents face-to-face, clear up the misunderstanding.

Too late to be politically depressed, too late to Romanticize a bad situation, too busy vindicating himself with his privacy. Although it's also clear that "clean" isn't really at the heart of the story.

After that, it didn't work. The Director of the Neighborhood Committee said that after knowing our request, he will communicate with the residents; after communicating with the residents, they are still very emotional and do not want to communicate with you. You are still in isolation for 14 days. In addition, why don't you have a residence permit. See, now that's the point of getting a residence permit. So also and the landlord communication, the landlord said now all out to fight the epidemic, the residence permit can not be expedited, you go back after 14 days, endure this 14 days to go back to stop.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Three

On February 1, most countries announced that foreigners or holders of passports issued by Hubei Province who had stayed in the province in the past 14 days had been refused entry. A little regret did not promise and friends to take advantage of the extended holiday to go abroad, the brain is filled with epidemic figures and words, always feel how can not enjoy going out, there is a sense of guilt in times of crisis abandoned the motherland. Wait until the "out" of the option was completely taken away, only to understand that the problem of self-love really need to change, foreign countries do not welcome you, your country may not like you.

One obvious benefit of a temporary home is that you can buy as much food as you eat, with little waste. The timing changed from checking your phone to watching the South Window pour light into the room, taking temperature readings in the morning and at night, and the day was over again.

Because of the weight of the outside world on Hubei Household Registration attention, life for the first time on their own regional awareness. In many ways, I've put the conventional wisdom on hold -- that citizenship doesn't define a person, that it's a very specific way of thinking about my family and friends in Wuhan, and wishing them well. In addition to repeated exhortations to do a good job of preventive measures, but will not take the initiative to discuss the epidemic with them. It's hard not to hear them say, don't watch it, don't watch the news, it'll be better.

Thinking that bad news is just a rumor, and waiting for the official announcement of good news (for example, Shuanghuanglian can suppress COVID-19) , or thinking that bad news is not necessarily a rumor, but because it will cause psychological trauma to oneself, the choice is closed-minded, it's hard to believe. Paying attention to those voices, is a must to do, after all, saw, can no longer blindfold said not to see. As for the price we really pay, what really counts as damage is some more heartbreak and tears, and we should know that. So when you are allowed to see, you have to look down, see the medical staff fighting in the front line, see the folk volunteers, see the caring people, see the journalists, see the help-seeking messages, see the evil intentions, see the righteousness and integrity. Save your strength, eat well, sleep well, and remember everything.

The disaster will pass. Of course the disaster will pass. But in reality, every good thing that can be rebuilt is the result of someone behind the scenes. After all, we have seen too many noble souls and too many moments of greatness in times of peril and challenges to our credibility, even when the price of "nobility" and "greatness" is never praiseworthy, but they deserve to be remembered.

Before going to bed, the director of the Neighborhood Committee called again, suggesting that we let the community to open a quarantine certificate. We said it would be impossible to open it, that we didn't need to be isolated, that other communities had no obligation to provide for us, and that we couldn't afford to cause any more trouble in our temporary room because of the kindness of our friends. After several rounds of negotiations, we both agreed that 14 days of isolation might not be enough to win the trust of the residents, so roommate offered to move out of the community voluntarily, but to save the time necessary to find a home and move, until then, I'd like to move back into the community as soon as possible so I can pack. So the chief said, "okay, I'm GonNa go talk to him. ".

Where will I be next month? This is the most frequent question I have asked myself in the two years I have lived in Beijing. This time, driven by the external situation, it seems that the question is a little more urgent.
